    {
      "id": "kVkAocIfrcg9wM98hZ0zv",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 317.2541825538076,
      "y": -13507.053102655149,
      "width": 2725.271484375,
      "height": 669.6705301277982,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aV",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1720877946,
      "version": 1762,
      "versionNonce": 1590481651,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. External Caching -> Most famous and most common in system design interview. Here we introduce a dedicated\n                    caching service like Redis or Memcache. It runs importantly on its own server and manages\n                    its own memory and its totally separate from our application or our database, and so when\n                    applicaton needs data it first check into cache if the data is found there, thats the cache\n                    hit and it returns data instantly superfast, if its not there cache miss it fallback to \n                    the database, fetch the data and store a copy of data back in the cache and also returns it\n                    back to the client\n\n    Nice thing here is in scaled system whihc might have multiple application server, all of them can share\nsame external cache.\nthis way once one server has fetched and cached the data, others can reuse it instantly,instead of hitting the\ndatabase separately, bcz this is global cache shared by all application servers.",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. External Caching -> Most famous and most common in system design interview. Here we introduce a dedicated\n                    caching service like Redis or Memcache. It runs importantly on its own server and manages\n                    its own memory and its totally separate from our application or our database, and so when\n                    applicaton needs data it first check into cache if the data is found there, thats the cache\n                    hit and it returns data instantly superfast, if its not there cache miss it fallback to \n                    the database, fetch the data and store a copy of data back in the cache and also returns it\n                    back to the client\n\n    Nice thing here is in scaled system whihc might have multiple application server, all of them can share\nsame external cache.\nthis way once one server has fetched and cached the data, others can reuse it instantly,instead of hitting the\ndatabase separately, bcz this is global cache shared by all application servers.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "n9LQoeNLJiyy-YcJT72SX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 416.7447691662472,
      "y": -9769.2783082829,
      "width": 2258.782958984375,
      "height": 1395.1469377662463,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aW",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1193804858,
      "version": 3189,
      "versionNonce": 1599359421,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. CDN (Content Delivery Network) -> CDN is a geographically distributed network of\n    servers that can cache content closer to our users. And we know this sounds fancy\nand fancier than it is. Its just putting servers around the world so that they are \nclose to people who need them, Here we are not optimizing for the difference between\nmemory and disk speeds like before instead we are optimizing for network latency, So\nwithout a CDN every single request has to travell all the way to our origin server.\nIf we have a server in Virginia and our user is in Australia then this round trip can\ntake 300 to 350 miliseconds that is huge. Specially when we are talking about disk\naccess being just 1 milisecond. with a CDN on the other hand the same request might hit\nan edge server that's just a few miles away which may be 20 to 40 miliseconds roundtrip,\nwhich is a huge difference, Now the way that it works is that when a user request some\nthing like an image that request goes to nearest CDN edge server like we just said.\nAnd if that image is already cached there, its returned immediately, thats the happy \ncase thats the cache hit, If not, if its a cache miss then CDN itself goes and fetches\nthat media or whatever we are looking from out origin server like S3 or whatever blob\nstorage we have, and then its going to return that back to the CDN, The CDN then will cache\nit, so that it has it for the next time and return it back to client.\n\nNow Modern CDNs, and this is something people oftentimes forget, they can do alot more than\njust cache static media, which is what they are known for, they can also cache public API\nresponses, of course HTML pages, run edge logic even to personalize content But as far as \na system design interview goes the most common and most impactful usecase is our media\ndelivery. So things like images, videos or static assests like files etc. that we want to \nload really quickly around the world. And so if we have global users who are accessing media\nregularily then a CDN is probably good fit for us.",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. CDN (Content Delivery Network) -> CDN is a geographically distributed network of\n    servers that can cache content closer to our users. And we know this sounds fancy\nand fancier than it is. Its just putting servers around the world so that they are \nclose to people who need them, Here we are not optimizing for the difference between\nmemory and disk speeds like before instead we are optimizing for network latency, So\nwithout a CDN every single request has to travell all the way to our origin server.\nIf we have a server in Virginia and our user is in Australia then this round trip can\ntake 300 to 350 miliseconds that is huge. Specially when we are talking about disk\naccess being just 1 milisecond. with a CDN on the other hand the same request might hit\nan edge server that's just a few miles away which may be 20 to 40 miliseconds roundtrip,\nwhich is a huge difference, Now the way that it works is that when a user request some\nthing like an image that request goes to nearest CDN edge server like we just said.\nAnd if that image is already cached there, its returned immediately, thats the happy \ncase thats the cache hit, If not, if its a cache miss then CDN itself goes and fetches\nthat media or whatever we are looking from out origin server like S3 or whatever blob\nstorage we have, and then its going to return that back to the CDN, The CDN then will cache\nit, so that it has it for the next time and return it back to client.\n\nNow Modern CDNs, and this is something people oftentimes forget, they can do alot more than\njust cache static media, which is what they are known for, they can also cache public API\nresponses, of course HTML pages, run edge logic even to personalize content But as far as \na system design interview goes the most common and most impactful usecase is our media\ndelivery. So things like images, videos or static assests like files etc. that we want to \nload really quickly around the world. And so if we have global users who are accessing media\nregularily then a CDN is probably good fit for us.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
