    {
      "id": "JsbboqMHC0R6jIOOkuQFu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 384.7653708807489,
      "y": -7126.555129786231,
      "width": 2283.335205078125,
      "height": 725.4764076384481,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ak",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1101149882,
      "version": 1705,
      "versionNonce": 1169756253,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "4. Client-side Caching -> this is when, data is stored directly on the user's device, either\nin the browser or in the app, which avoids unnecessary network calls. In web app that might \nbe http cache or localstoratge within the browser itself, For mobile apps this could be data\nkept in memory or even written to the local disk or device. and its nice due to it is super \nfast. The data never leaves the device. but it comes with downside off course, thats we have \nless control over it, Data can go stale, validation, freshness, all of that is a bit harder.\n\nusually it is userful when our system involves some offline functionality or client heavy \nworkloads.\n\nExample -> If a browser is reusing images it already downloaded or an app like Strava caching\nyou run data while you are offline. and then syncing it once we reconnected, this is least\nimp for our system design interviews.",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "4. Client-side Caching -> this is when, data is stored directly on the user's device, either\nin the browser or in the app, which avoids unnecessary network calls. In web app that might \nbe http cache or localstoratge within the browser itself, For mobile apps this could be data\nkept in memory or even written to the local disk or device. and its nice due to it is super \nfast. The data never leaves the device. but it comes with downside off course, thats we have \nless control over it, Data can go stale, validation, freshness, all of that is a bit harder.\n\nusually it is userful when our system involves some offline functionality or client heavy \nworkloads.\n\nExample -> If a browser is reusing images it already downloaded or an app like Strava caching\nyou run data while you are offline. and then syncing it once we reconnected, this is least\nimp for our system design interviews.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
