      "text": "2.Read from \nDB as fallback",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "JCiZpp8reN7SaCBeJYGBl",
      "originalText": "2.Read from \nDB as fallback",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "PBWGIs2eGeG0P_SgrxwOD",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 463.1273657349112,
      "y": -3074.648604085123,
      "width": 2382.077392578125,
      "height": 1451.1950027768962,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0Q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 286658534,
      "version": 3066,
      "versionNonce": 220569565,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Write-through -> With write through application actually writes directly to cache first, and\n       then the cache synchronously writes that data to database before it returs to the user. So\n        the write is not considered complete until both the cache and the database have been \n    updated. \n   In Practice this means that we need a caching library or a framework for the part that will \ninteract with Database that supports this write through behaviour something that know to trigger\nour database write logic automatically because tools like Redis or Memcache they dont natively\nsupport this, So we need to either handle this logic from ourself in our application code by \nwriting to both at the same time and there is lot of complications that come from that or we \nneed to library something like SpringCache or HazelCache which can automatically do that write\nthrough for us.\n\nTrade off -> 1 Slower writes due to we need to wait for these to happen\n        2 We pollute our cache with all this data that may never be read again\n        3 It also suffers with Dual write problem, this would be that if the cache update\n   succeed but the database write fails or vice versa then the two enter in inconsistent\n   state. So we need fancy retry logic error handling all of these things to deal with this, \n   In Distributed system this perfect consistency is incredibly hard to achieve , So there\nare all sorts of complications.\n\nIn System Design interview , Write through cache is much less common than the cache aside\nbecause it requires all the speciallized infrastructure and has all these tricky edge cases\naround consistency. So we would really only bring it up when reads must always return the\nfresh data and our system can tolerate some slightly slower writes, if thats the case this \ncould be a good fit. But if our mind is going in this direction really be sure that we can\nconvince ourself that cache aside or some other designed system doesn't satisfy our usecase",
      "fontSize": 44.65215393159681,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Write-through -> With write through application actually writes directly to cache first, and\n       then the cache synchronously writes that data to database before it returs to the user. So\n        the write is not considered complete until both the cache and the database have been \n    updated. \n   In Practice this means that we need a caching library or a framework for the part that will \ninteract with Database that supports this write through behaviour something that know to trigger\nour database write logic automatically because tools like Redis or Memcache they dont natively\nsupport this, So we need to either handle this logic from ourself in our application code by \nwriting to both at the same time and there is lot of complications that come from that or we \nneed to library something like SpringCache or HazelCache which can automatically do that write\nthrough for us.\n\nTrade off -> 1 Slower writes due to we need to wait for these to happen\n        2 We pollute our cache with all this data that may never be read again\n        3 It also suffers with Dual write problem, this would be that if the cache update\n   succeed but the database write fails or vice versa then the two enter in inconsistent\n   state. So we need fancy retry logic error handling all of these things to deal with this, \n   In Distributed system this perfect consistency is incredibly hard to achieve , So there\nare all sorts of complications.\n\nIn System Design interview , Write through cache is much less common than the cache aside\nbecause it requires all the speciallized infrastructure and has all these tricky edge cases\naround consistency. So we would really only bring it up when reads must always return the\nfresh data and our system can tolerate some slightly slower writes, if thats the case this \ncould be a good fit. But if our mind is going in this direction really be sure that we can\nconvince ourself that cache aside or some other designed system doesn't satisfy our usecase",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
