    {
      "id": "nFOuDDXoovV9eJERNSbcA",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 658.252421578572,
      "y": 644.2829174070284,
      "width": 2283.335205078125,
      "height": 558.0587751064985,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0s",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1563335398,
      "version": 1482,
      "versionNonce": 235383069,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "4. Read-through -> Its similar to cache aside, except that the cache handles the\ndatabase lookup instead of application. And so on a cache miss whereas before the application\nserver went and read from the database and updated the cache and return the value now the\ncache itself is going to do that. So we try to read from the cache if we miss the cache\ngoes and requests the data from the database stores it in the cache and return back to the\napplication server. \n\nWe basically think about it like a cache aside but with the cache acting as a proxy. And \nthis is essentially how CDN's work, when we have a CDN miss it fetches from the origin server\ncaches the results and then return to the client and servers it next time.",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "4. Read-through -> Its similar to cache aside, except that the cache handles the\ndatabase lookup instead of application. And so on a cache miss whereas before the application\nserver went and read from the database and updated the cache and return the value now the\ncache itself is going to do that. So we try to read from the cache if we miss the cache\ngoes and requests the data from the database stores it in the cache and return back to the\napplication server. \n\nWe basically think about it like a cache aside but with the cache acting as a proxy. And \nthis is essentially how CDN's work, when we have a CDN miss it fetches from the origin server\ncaches the results and then return to the client and servers it next time.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
