      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Common Issues / Deep Dives->\n",
      "fontSize": 62.50258281192785,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Common Issues / Deep Dives->\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "7KgXw0qhjY8H5Y8yCazs_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 542.5927766461591,
      "y": 4943.267149640544,
      "width": 2553.406982421875,
      "height": 1171.923427723647,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1Q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 888399034,
      "version": 1991,
      "versionNonce": 1797413085,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Cache Stampede (Thundering Herd) (18:00) ->  This happens when a popular cache entry expires via that\n    TTL. And suddenly flood of requests all try to rebuild that cache at the same time. And so\neven if the window lasts just a second, every single one of those cache misses is going to hit\nour database turning one query into thousand or even million and ultimately overwhelming our DB.\n\nExample -> Imagine we have a website we cached the home page feed with TTL 60 sec and we get\n100 1000 request every second till 60 sec everything is fine but after 60 sec it expires, Now \nall the 100000 request will go to cache and cache miss will be there so they all will hit the\nDB.\n\nThere are two common ways by which we can prevent this\ni request collesing or single flight -> when a request tries to build the same cache key or\n    when there are multiple requests try to rebuild the same cache key, then only the first\n    one should work and rest of them should just wait for the results to come in and then \n    read from the cache\n\nii Cache Warming -> the way of working is instead of waiting for popular keys to expire , \nwaiting that full 60 sec, we can proactively refresh them just before they do so the the \n55 sec we will go and refresh the feed and that give another 60 sec and preventing it from \never expiring. just keep refreshing it every 55 sec. So that remain fresh not stale and never\ncaused thundering herd.",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Cache Stampede (Thundering Herd) (18:00) ->  This happens when a popular cache entry expires via that\n    TTL. And suddenly flood of requests all try to rebuild that cache at the same time. And so\neven if the window lasts just a second, every single one of those cache misses is going to hit\nour database turning one query into thousand or even million and ultimately overwhelming our DB.\n\nExample -> Imagine we have a website we cached the home page feed with TTL 60 sec and we get\n100 1000 request every second till 60 sec everything is fine but after 60 sec it expires, Now \nall the 100000 request will go to cache and cache miss will be there so they all will hit the\nDB.\n\nThere are two common ways by which we can prevent this\ni request collesing or single flight -> when a request tries to build the same cache key or\n    when there are multiple requests try to rebuild the same cache key, then only the first\n    one should work and rest of them should just wait for the results to come in and then \n    read from the cache\n\nii Cache Warming -> the way of working is instead of waiting for popular keys to expire , \nwaiting that full 60 sec, we can proactively refresh them just before they do so the the \n55 sec we will go and refresh the feed and that give another 60 sec and preventing it from \never expiring. just keep refreshing it every 55 sec. So that remain fresh not stale and never\ncaused thundering herd.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
