      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Overwhelmed!",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Overwhelmed!",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ImyFobX3Jva_ngYsZQ_8y",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 559.5776634324676,
      "y": 7197.426311990548,
      "width": 2504.302978515625,
      "height": 1116.117550212997,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b21",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1914259578,
      "version": 2348,
      "versionNonce": 1680844979,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Cache Consistency -> Most common issue, this happend when cache and the database could return\ndifferent values for the same data. And its really easy to occur, Because most system read from\nthe cache but they write to the database. And so this creates this short window depending on our\neviction policy we can have stale data in cache.\n\nExample -> We have some social network and a user updates their profile picture, And that new\nvalue is written to the database but the old one still sitting on cache and now so other users\nwho are requesting are hitting the cache and they are getting stale image, thats bad, and they\ncontinue to read this value untill this ends up being evicted for some reason, there is no \nperfect fix to this, it very much depends on how fresh our data needs to be and that is a case\nby case basis But there is some common strategies in order to answer the question if our\ninterviewer asks about\n\nsolution i -> invalidate on write -> if consistency really important here then when profile picture\ncame and updated in DB we can also go and delete that key proactively from the cache, next read \ncomes in cache miss and data will come from database update to cache and return to client no stale\ndata.\n\nsolution ii -> Short TTL 60 sec -> As we know that changes often for sometime its fine and eventually \n    good data. ",
      "fontSize": 44.64470200851988,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Cache Consistency -> Most common issue, this happend when cache and the database could return\ndifferent values for the same data. And its really easy to occur, Because most system read from\nthe cache but they write to the database. And so this creates this short window depending on our\neviction policy we can have stale data in cache.\n\nExample -> We have some social network and a user updates their profile picture, And that new\nvalue is written to the database but the old one still sitting on cache and now so other users\nwho are requesting are hitting the cache and they are getting stale image, thats bad, and they\ncontinue to read this value untill this ends up being evicted for some reason, there is no \nperfect fix to this, it very much depends on how fresh our data needs to be and that is a case\nby case basis But there is some common strategies in order to answer the question if our\ninterviewer asks about\n\nsolution i -> invalidate on write -> if consistency really important here then when profile picture\ncame and updated in DB we can also go and delete that key proactively from the cache, next read \ncomes in cache miss and data will come from database update to cache and return to client no stale\ndata.\n\nsolution ii -> Short TTL 60 sec -> As we know that changes often for sometime its fine and eventually \n    good data. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
