    {
      "id": "uuvou165ngymEWDJSroyU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 347.8664846273614,
      "y": -11413.879170655377,
      "width": 2354.351806640625,
      "height": 874.7631989310473,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2qV",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 564209786,
      "version": 2332,
      "versionNonce": 1915371443,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. In-process Caching -> Modern Appllication is usually run on very big machine now a days, they \n                        have plenty of memory and we can use some ammount of memory in order to cache\n            data inside the process. This is imp because its by far the fastest kind of caching. We \n            don't have to go and have an expensive network hop like external caching. We dont have to\n            hit external network call for cache, data is inside same memory only. But of course it comes\n            with tradeoffs as well.and the main trade off is that unlike the external cach each app\n            server has its own inprocess memory and this means if one server cache has something\n            others can't see that. So we can end up with these inconsistencies or even wasted memory\n            if we are not too careful.\n\n     the chances are at least in the context of system design interview that we probably we don't need\nto bring this up unless we are talking about Low Level optimizations or have a use case where ultra low\nlatency matters\n\nFor Example -> If we need to cache config data or small lookup tables that every single request depends\n                upon then caching within application server make sense. But Our default should remain\n                external caching.",
      "fontSize": 41.165327008519874,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. In-process Caching -> Modern Appllication is usually run on very big machine now a days, they \n                        have plenty of memory and we can use some ammount of memory in order to cache\n            data inside the process. This is imp because its by far the fastest kind of caching. We \n            don't have to go and have an expensive network hop like external caching. We dont have to\n            hit external network call for cache, data is inside same memory only. But of course it comes\n            with tradeoffs as well.and the main trade off is that unlike the external cach each app\n            server has its own inprocess memory and this means if one server cache has something\n            others can't see that. So we can end up with these inconsistencies or even wasted memory\n            if we are not too careful.\n\n     the chances are at least in the context of system design interview that we probably we don't need\nto bring this up unless we are talking about Low Level optimizations or have a use case where ultra low\nlatency matters\n\nFor Example -> If we need to cache config data or small lookup tables that every single request depends\n                upon then caching within application server make sense. But Our default should remain\n                external caching.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "vMALfObJU-JEtSuPmCtya",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2525.052986594888,
      "y": -12521.793874020888,
      "width": 402.6636400918302,
      "height": 171.45330105750918,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
