    },
    {
      "id": "3vRaLNyHzEygUnE9L-HsS",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 3411.3804235471453,
      "y": -9760.054194890552,
      "width": 3900.598876953125,
      "height": 12870,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2u",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 66372807,
      "version": 109,
      "versionNonce": 1825427795,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1️⃣ “How do we handle stale data in CDN?”\n\nFirst, accept this truth:\n\nCDNs trade freshness for speed.\nStale data is not a bug — it’s a controlled decision.\n\n🔹 Technique 1: TTL (Time To Live) — most common\n\n👉 Every cached object has an expiry time.\n\nExample:\n\nEvent poster image → TTL = 24 hours\nSeat layout JSON → TTL = 30 seconds\n\n\nHow it works:\nCDN serves cached content until TTL expires\nAfter expiry → CDN fetches fresh data from origin\nThinking style\n“This image doesn’t change often, so I’m okay if users see an old version for 1 day.”\n\nUsed for:\n\nImages\nVideos\nStatic assets\n\n\n🔹 Technique 2: Cache Invalidation (Force refresh)\n\nWhen you know data changed, you explicitly tell CDN:\n“Hey, delete this cached object NOW.”\n\nExample:\n\nEvent poster updated\nOrganizer changes banner\n\nYou call:\nInvalidate /events/123/poster.png\nDownside:\n\nCostly\nNot instant everywhere (takes seconds–minutes)\n\nSo:\n\nUse sparingly, not for frequently changing data.\n\n🔹 Technique 3: Versioned URLs (Best practice 🔥)\nInstead of invalidating:\nposter.png\n\nUse:\n\nposter_v3.png\nposter_hash_abc123.png\n\n\nNow:\nNew content = new URL\nCDN treats it as a new object\nOld cache dies naturally\nThis is industry standard for static media.\n\n🔹 Technique 4: Stale-While-Revalidate (Modern CDNs)\n\nThis is where CDNs get smart.\n\nFlow:\n\nCDN serves slightly stale data immediately\nIn background → fetches fresh data from origin\nNext user gets fresh content\nResult:\nNo slow user experience\nData eventually becomes fresh\nPerfect for:\nPublic APIs\nHTML pages\nEvent listings\n\n2️⃣ “First user will always be slow, right?”\n\nShort answer: Not always — and we can reduce it a LOT.\n\nYes, cache miss = CDN → Origin → CDN → User, which adds latency.\nBut we have strategies to hide or reduce this pain.\n\n🔹 Strategy 1: Pre-warming the CDN (Very important)\n\nBefore traffic hits:\nUpload images\nHit CDN URLs once programmatically\n\nExample:\nWhen event is created → pre-fetch event images via CDN\n\nNow:\nFirst real user gets a cache hit ✔️\nUsed for:\nBig events\nHome page assets\nCampaign banners\n\n🔹 Strategy 2: Accept slow first user (because it’s rare)\n\nThink practically:\n“One slow request out of 1 million is acceptable.”\nCDNs are designed for:\nAmortized performance\nMajority-fast, minority-slow\nThis is totally acceptable in interviews.\n\n🔹 Strategy 3: Origin close to CDN (multi-region origin)\n\nInstead of:\n\nAll CDNs → Virginia origin\n\n\nYou can have:\n\nCDN Asia → Singapore origin\nCDN Europe → Frankfurt origin\n\n\nSo even cache misses are not cross-continent.\n\n🔹 Strategy 4: Cache only what makes sense\n\nNever cache:\nBooking APIs\nSeat availability\nPayment responses\nCache aggressively:\nImages\nVideos\nEvent metadata\nPublic search results (short TTL)\n\n3️⃣ How you explain this cleanly in an interview 💯\nSenior-level answer (very crisp)\n\n“CDNs may serve stale data, which we control using TTLs, cache invalidation, and versioned URLs.\nFor frequently changing data, we use short TTLs or avoid caching entirely.\nFor static media, versioning is preferred to avoid invalidation costs.\n\nWhile the first cache miss may be slower, we mitigate this via CDN pre-warming, multi-region origins, and accepting occasional cold starts since the vast majority of requests benefit from caching.”\n\n4️⃣ One-liner mental model (remember this)\n\nTTL → “How stale am I okay with?”\nInvalidation → “I changed something NOW”\nVersioning → “New content, new URL”\nCold miss → “Paid once, saved millions of times”\n\nIf you want, next we can:\n\nConnect CDN + cache + DB in one request flow\nExplain why CDN ≠ Redis\nOr prepare CDN cross-questions interviewers love to ask\nJust say the word 😄\n\nSo you are saying in CDN we just cache media which not  frequently changed then for data every time origin server will hit?\n\n\nShort answer: No — not “every time” 🙂\nLong answer (the important one): CDNs can cache data too, but only certain kinds of data, in certain ways.\n\nLet’s break this cleanly and kill the confusion.\n\n1️⃣ What is always safe to cache in a CDN?\n👉 Rarely changing, non-critical content\nExamples:\nImages, videos, CSS, JS\nEvent posters\nStatic HTML pages (landing pages)\n\nHere:\nLong TTL\nVersioned URLs\nNear-zero risk\n\nThis is why people say: “CDN is for media” — it’s the default mental model, not the full truth.\n\n2️⃣ Can CDNs cache “data” (API responses)?\n✅ Yes — but only when ALL these are true\n\nThink like this:\n“If this data is slightly stale, will my system break?”\n\nGood candidates for CDN data caching\n\nPublic, unauthenticated APIs\nRead-heavy endpoints\nNon-critical freshness\n\nExamples:\n\nGET /events\nGET /events/123/details\nGET /trending-events\nGET /categories\n\n\n3️⃣ What should NEVER be cached in CDN?\n\n👉 Anything where correctness > speed\n\nExamples:\nSeat availability\nBooking status\nPayment APIs\nUser profile\n\nAuthenticated user data\n\nFor these:\n\nCDN passes request directly to origin\n\nNo caching\n\nStrong consistency guaranteed\n\nHere:\n\nYes, origin is hit every time.\nAnd that’s intentional.\n\n4️⃣ Think in layers (THIS is the key insight)\n\nMost seniors think CDN = “media cache”.\nArchitects think in layers:\n\nUser\n ↓\nCDN (edge cache – coarse, fast, global)\n ↓\nApplication Cache (Redis – fresher)\n ↓\nDatabase (source of truth)\n\n\nSo for “data”:\n\nCDN may cache for seconds\nRedis caches for milliseconds\nDB is last resort\nResult:\n\nOrigin DB is NOT hit every time\nCDN is just the outermost layer\n\n5️⃣ Concrete example (ticket system)\nSearching events\nUser → CDN (cache hit?) → return\n              ↓ miss\n            Origin → Redis → DB\n\n\nCDN TTL: 30 sec\nRedis TTL: 5 sec\nDB hit: rare\nBooking ticket\nUser → CDN (no cache) → Booking Service → DB\n\nAlways origin\nStrong consistency\nNo CDN caching\n\n6️⃣ Interview-ready summary (say this verbatim)\n\n“We primarily use CDN for static media, but it can also cache public, read-heavy API responses with short TTLs.\nFor correctness-critical data like bookings and payments, requests always go to the origin.\nCDN acts as the outermost caching layer, reducing global latency, while application caches and databases handle fresher data.”\n\n7️⃣ One-line rule to remember 🧠\n\nIf wrong data is acceptable → CDN cache it\nIf wrong data breaks business → always hit origin\n\n",
