    {
      "id": "4HVgr4LBab-Gkeo9FE7lR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 525.3373221754769,
      "y": -13684.890241880532,
      "width": 2078.9990234375,
      "height": 90,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4m",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 227215056,
      "version": 209,
      "versionNonce": 1056565021,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "There is a few different layers in our system where caching can live, Each of which have their own set of\ntrade-offs of course.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "There is a few different layers in our system where caching can live, Each of which have their own set of\ntrade-offs of course.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "FZN6MTob2V6HbX0XRgxnx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 668.9827785183716,
      "y": 2867.1953029810174,
      "width": 2118.59912109375,
      "height": 180,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 143134917,
      "version": 479,
      "versionNonce": 860972339,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "One trade off of storing data in memory cache(RAM) instead of on Disk is that memory is limited , we can't\nfit all whole data inside cache. At least we usually can't, Hence we need a strategy for deciding what to \nkeep and what to remove as new data comes in and that exactly what our evection policies do. They determine\nwhich item stay in the cache and which one gets replaced when it fills up.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "One trade off of storing data in memory cache(RAM) instead of on Disk is that memory is limited , we can't\nfit all whole data inside cache. At least we usually can't, Hence we need a strategy for deciding what to \nkeep and what to remove as new data comes in and that exactly what our evection policies do. They determine\nwhich item stay in the cache and which one gets replaced when it fills up.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "YjtXQ79dTI5WEeMVm6-vQ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 821.2718410183716,
      "y": 4311.203115481017,
      "width": 2059.19873046875,
      "height": 450,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4u",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1666540235,
      "version": 798,
      "versionNonce": 1892219773,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Adding cache introduce a whole new set of challenges, and there challenges interviewers love to \nask about, And do there is a famous saying in Computer Science that some of us might have heard and\nits that there is only two hard problems in computer science\n1 Naming things\n2 Cache Invalidation\n\nSecond one exists with the reason, Once we start caching new problems start to show up. Things like\nuneven load, stale data or unexpected spikes in traffic.\nSo we are going to go few of the most common issues, that we should be ready to talk about in interview.\nThe ones that interviewers will kind of be the most likely to may be probe into.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Adding cache introduce a whole new set of challenges, and there challenges interviewers love to \nask about, And do there is a famous saying in Computer Science that some of us might have heard and\nits that there is only two hard problems in computer science\n1 Naming things\n2 Cache Invalidation\n\nSecond one exists with the reason, Once we start caching new problems start to show up. Things like\nuneven load, stale data or unexpected spikes in traffic.\nSo we are going to go few of the most common issues, that we should be ready to talk about in interview.\nThe ones that interviewers will kind of be the most likely to may be probe into.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "1n92Pi0-pCZ22YBBa2XY8",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 371.4225675538096,
      "y": 9587.916759933723,
      "width": 2779.48388671875,
      "height": 1298.9453124999998,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4v",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 644611436,
      "version": 2217,
      "versionNonce": 418662099,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771307885705,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. Hot Keys -> other common issue  which we have seen come up in many of the videos if we watched any of\nthe content is called Hot Keys.\nHot keys are cache entries that get way more traffic than anyone else even if our overall cache hit rate\nis great everything working as planned that single key can still become a large bottleneck for our system.\n\nExample -> we are building Twitter X and everyone is viewing Taylors Swift profile, that cache key for her\nuser data could be receiving million of requests per second and that one key can overload a single Redis\nnode or Shard even thour that shard or cache is technically working as expected, Of course this is not\njust the problem with Caching,Database can have hot rows or partitions as well but its a common follow up\nquestion in interview once we introduce caching,Especially if we introduce caching in order to scale our\nreads So caching does increase our overall read throughput, we are now hitting memory as supposed to disk\nbut it doesn't completely solve the problem if there is one piece of data that is so overwhelming popular\nlike Taylor swift here.\n\nThere are couple of things that we can do -> \ni -> most common solution is to just replicate the hot keys, and so if everybody is trying to know about\n    Taylor Swift, we can replicate Taylor Swift\n\nii -> solution is we can add local fallback cache basically we can use in process caching idea in order to \n    add a cache, this way we can keep extemely Hot values like Taylor Swift in the apps memory so repeated\nrequest dont even ever need to go and hit the redis we just store them locally here.\nIN overall Caching helps us to scale reads but it doesn't make our system magically infinite",
      "fontSize": 47.23437499999999,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. Hot Keys -> other common issue  which we have seen come up in many of the videos if we watched any of\nthe content is called Hot Keys.\nHot keys are cache entries that get way more traffic than anyone else even if our overall cache hit rate\nis great everything working as planned that single key can still become a large bottleneck for our system.\n\nExample -> we are building Twitter X and everyone is viewing Taylors Swift profile, that cache key for her\nuser data could be receiving million of requests per second and that one key can overload a single Redis\nnode or Shard even thour that shard or cache is technically working as expected, Of course this is not\njust the problem with Caching,Database can have hot rows or partitions as well but its a common follow up\nquestion in interview once we introduce caching,Especially if we introduce caching in order to scale our\nreads So caching does increase our overall read throughput, we are now hitting memory as supposed to disk\nbut it doesn't completely solve the problem if there is one piece of data that is so overwhelming popular\nlike Taylor swift here.\n\nThere are couple of things that we can do -> \ni -> most common solution is to just replicate the hot keys, and so if everybody is trying to know about\n    Taylor Swift, we can replicate Taylor Swift\n\nii -> solution is we can add local fallback cache basically we can use in process caching idea in order to \n    add a cache, this way we can keep extemely Hot values like Taylor Swift in the apps memory so repeated\nrequest dont even ever need to go and hit the redis we just store them locally here.\nIN overall Caching helps us to scale reads but it doesn't make our system magically infinite",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
