      "text": "Normal Database here means such as Relational Database, they are built for these small frequently\nchanging record that need rich queries and things like Join, They are not made to handle large, mostly\nstatic file\n\nImaging we are storing profile photos right alongside all of the other user information thats in our\nUser table. It might feel convenient for us. We have users we are storing their roles, names and all of\ndiff things and then additionaly their profile image. But Postgress we can use as example of RDBMS here,\npacks all of these rows internally into 8KB pages. And if we were going to have a 4 MB image, that going\nto span 500 whole pages. Why is having 500 pages very bad.\nImagine simple query like, we want to fetch top 50 users, Even though we only want a small piece of the data,\nhaving these large images stored alongside of the user data is going to create a ton of extra overhead.\nThe database has to manage and potentially access these huge files, these many Megabyte(MB) of pages we have\nnow, and this is going to impact things like performace, increase memory pressure, slow down what should be\nfast and simple queries. But thats not the only problem. We also need to consider replication as another issue.\nWhen we replicate data across multiple database server for either backups or scaling that 4MB of blob has to\nbe copied to every single replica with each write, which is going to create ton of lag and consume massive\nbandwidth. Then there is notioin of backups more specifically where these 4 MB images are going to be \nincluded in those maybe nightly backups that we run.\nAnd so we are going to turn then in a restoration process, which should only take maybe a couple of minutes \ninto many long hours. So we can picture ourself, we are working we are up late, our database has gone down, \nour users are frustated and we are trying to restore from a backup, but our backup is huge it is loaded with\nall of these static files, and so restoration of our database is going to take many hours, hence traditional\nDB like RDBMS , they choke on blobs both in term of performance and in terms of cost. this is where object \nstorage comes into play. We should be storing them stricktly speaking in our object or blob storage",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Normal Database here means such as Relational Database, they are built for these small frequently\nchanging record that need rich queries and things like Join, They are not made to handle large, mostly\nstatic file\n\nImaging we are storing profile photos right alongside all of the other user information thats in our\nUser table. It might feel convenient for us. We have users we are storing their roles, names and all of\ndiff things and then additionaly their profile image. But Postgress we can use as example of RDBMS here,\npacks all of these rows internally into 8KB pages. And if we were going to have a 4 MB image, that going\nto span 500 whole pages. Why is having 500 pages very bad.\nImagine simple query like, we want to fetch top 50 users, Even though we only want a small piece of the data,\nhaving these large images stored alongside of the user data is going to create a ton of extra overhead.\nThe database has to manage and potentially access these huge files, these many Megabyte(MB) of pages we have\nnow, and this is going to impact things like performace, increase memory pressure, slow down what should be\nfast and simple queries. But thats not the only problem. We also need to consider replication as another issue.\nWhen we replicate data across multiple database server for either backups or scaling that 4MB of blob has to\nbe copied to every single replica with each write, which is going to create ton of lag and consume massive\nbandwidth. Then there is notioin of backups more specifically where these 4 MB images are going to be \nincluded in those maybe nightly backups that we run.\nAnd so we are going to turn then in a restoration process, which should only take maybe a couple of minutes \ninto many long hours. So we can picture ourself, we are working we are up late, our database has gone down, \nour users are frustated and we are trying to restore from a backup, but our backup is huge it is loaded with\nall of these static files, and so restoration of our database is going to take many hours, hence traditional\nDB like RDBMS , they choke on blobs both in term of performance and in terms of cost. this is where object \nstorage comes into play. We should be storing them stricktly speaking in our object or blob storage",
